Kanu is using dialogue and consensus to identify aspirants who will vie in most parts of the Rift Valley.Nominated Senator Zipporah Kittony has said party officials have been encouraging aspirants vying for the same seat to agree among themselves, instead of going through the nominations.She said they have identified aspirants in Trans Nzoia, West Pokot and Elgeyo Marakwet counties.&ldquo;Many people have been claiming that Kanu died in this region, but they will be shocked that, come August 8, we will win many seats across the country,&rdquo; Kittony said on Saturday.She spoke after meeting aspirants in Kitale.Kittony said the party recognised the role of each aspirant, hence the need for them to agree through consensus to promote unity and strengthen the party.Baringo Senator Gideon Moi is among those who will get direct tickets. Kanu has also issued a direct ticket to former Inspector General of Police David Kimaiyo, who is vying for Elgeyo Marakwet senator.Jepkosgey Kobilo has also received a direct nomination to run for the woman representative seat in Elgeyo Marakwet, while West Pokot Senator John Lonyangapuo will get the ticket to run for governor.Former Information minister Samuel Poghisio will vie for the West Pokot Senate seat.Kanu has also issued a direct ticket to Jonathan Bii to run for the Soy seat in Uasin Gishu.Party official Paul Kibet said in most areas, aspirants have agreed to use consensus in identifying those to vie for seats, mostly those for MCAs.The opposition parties will also give direct tickets to most aspirants in the Rift Valley, which is a perceived Jubilee stronghold.The ODM and ANC parties have already issued direct tickets to some aspirants, including David Songok, who will vie for the Turbo seat in Uasin Gishu and Tom Murgor for senator in the same county.ANC has issued a direct ticket to Chepkok Moira to run for Uasin Gishu woman representative.ODM official Kipkorir Menjo yesterday said the party has postponed primaries to tomorrow in the region.He said the opposition parties have few aspirants in the region. &ldquo;After the primaries, we will have strong aspirants to face off with Jubilee,&rdquo; Menjo said. Minority leader in the Uasin Gishu assembly Ramadhan Ali has been the only ODM MCA in the region, representing Kiplombe ward, where he will be defending the seat.